Japan, Australia Stock Futures Gain as U.S Confidence Rises

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-06-09T23:19:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/japan-australian-stock-futures-advance-as-u-s-consumer-confidence-rises.html
Japanese and Australian stock
futures rose as U.S. consumer confidence improved, easing
concern that the global recovery will falter.  American depositary receipts of  Canon Inc. (7751) , the world’s
biggest camera maker by sales, rose 0.7 percent from the closing
price in Tokyo. Nissan Motor Co., a carmaker that earns more
than a third of its revenue from  North America , advanced 0.7
percent after the yen weakened against the dollar, boosting the
earnings outlook for the exporter. ADRs of  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) ,
Australia’s No. 1 oil producer, advanced 0.9 percent after  oil
prices  increased.  “The  U.S. economy  isn’t strong, but it’s improving,” said
Juichi Wako, a senior strategist at Tokyo-based Nomura Holdings
Inc. “Investors are trying to resist the urge to stay clear of
risk assets so you’ll probably see some bargain hunting.”  Futures on  Japan ’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,520 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 9,480
in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,510 in
Osaka, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX
200 Index rose 0.5 percent today.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index rose 0.1 percent
today. In  New York  yesterday, the index gained 0.7 percent,
snapping a six-day streak of declines, after a report showed
that consumer confidence rose last week for the third
consecutive time as lower gasoline prices lifted Americans’
outlook on their finances.  Consumer Comfort  The Bloomberg Consumer Comfort Index climbed to minus 45.9
in the period to June 5, the best showing since the end of April,
from the prior week’s minus 47.1. Across income groups,
sentiment improved the most among people making less than
$50,000 a year.  A separate report showed that the U.S. trade deficit
unexpectedly narrowed in April, reflecting a plunge in auto and
oil imports combined with record exports.  The dollar appreciated to as high as 80.47 yen today in
 Tokyo , compared with 80.09 at the close of stock trading
yesterday, boosting the value of overseas income for Japanese
exporters.  Crude oil for July delivery rose 1.2 percent to $101.93 a
barrel in New York yesterday, the highest settlement since May
31, after OPEC failed to reach an accord on output targets for
the first time in at least 20 years. Ministers from the 12-
nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were unable
to come to agreement in five hours of talks in Vienna yesterday.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index slid 3.7 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with a gain of 2.5 percent by the
S&P 500 and a drop of 1.5 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 13.4 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 13 times for the  S&P 500  and
11 times for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters on this story:
